03983nam a22007095i 9780813562605DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20132013nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2013005975  a97808135626057 a10.36019/97808135626052doi  a(DE-B1597)529251  a(OCoLC)864749917  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aHV6025b.P665 2013 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a303.62231 aPresser, Lois, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhy We Harm /cLois Presser. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (182 p.) :b2 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Issues in Crime and Society0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCriminologists are primarily concerned with the analysis of actions that violate existing laws. But a growing number have begun analyzing crimes as actions that inflict harm, regardless of the applicability of legal sanctions. Even as they question standard definitions of crime as law-breaking, scholars of crime have few theoretical frameworks with which to understand the etiology of harmful action. In Why We Harm, Lois Presser scrutinizes accounts of acts as diverse as genocide, environmental degradation, war, torture, terrorism, homicide, rape, and meat-eating in order to develop an original theoretical framework with which to consider harmful actions and their causes. In doing so, this timely book presents a general theory of harm, revealing the commonalities between actions that impose suffering and cause destruction. Harm is built on stories in which the targets of harm are reduced to one-dimensional characters—sometimes a dangerous foe, sometimes much more benign, but still a projection of our own concerns and interests. In our stories of harm, we are licensed to do the harmful deed and, at the same time, are powerless to act differently. Chapter by chapter, Presser examines statements made by perpetrators of a wide variety of harmful actions. Appearing vastly different from one another at first glance, Presser identifies the logics they share that motivate, legitimize, and sustain them. From that point, she maps out strategies for reducing harm.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aCrimexSociological aspects. 0aCriminology. 0aViolence. 0aViolent crimesxPsychological aspects. 0aViolent crimeszPsychological aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081356260540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813562605423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813562605/original  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK